We have arrived at the very last session. of the day. The very last session of the con, I hope we have all learned a number of things, at least half of which will stick in our minds, the rest of it.


2
00:00:22.955 --> 00:00:40.955
Maybe when we watch the talks again on YouTube. So we have two more talks. And then, you know, whatever festivities we choose to close this thing out with. So my ask is that we… Lock in.


3
00:00:40.955 --> 00:00:47.955
Pay attention to the last couple speakers. Eat our last few cookies.


4
00:00:47.955 --> 00:00:53.955
Start to quiet down, take our conversations out of the room.


5
00:00:53.955 --> 00:01:06.955
Downstairs to the overflow space. Uh, and give our last couple speakers, uh, the same respect we've given to the rest of them. Uh, up next, so the two, the two talks that we have to close ourselves out are kind of…


6
00:01:06.955 --> 00:01:32.955
Uh, a little bit of a grab bag, uh, so we're gonna first, uh, first talk about, uh, the AI automation boundary, and then, uh, the last… talk is detection and deception from the folks at Grey Noise. But first, please welcome Arthi.


7
00:01:32.955 --> 00:01:49.955
Hello, can everyone hear me? All right. Okay, so I'm gonna try to keep y'all engaged for the next 20 minutes. I know it's been a long day, but in this session, I'm going to be talking about exploring the AI automation boundary for threat hunting.


8
00:01:49.955 --> 00:02:02.955
My name is Arthi Nagarajan, I am a software engineer at Datadog. I work closely with internal threat intelligence and detection teams to productionize and scale up their security processes.


9
00:02:02.955 --> 00:02:18.955
Over the past 6 to 9 months, we've been developing an AI-powered threat hunting tool called the Hunting Copilot. I'll share the lessons we learned along the way and how our understanding of the automation boundary for AI in threat hunting evolved through real-world use.


10
00:02:18.955 --> 00:02:25.955
Our goal is to equip our internal threat hunting teams with tools to accelerate their hunts.


11
00:02:25.955 --> 00:02:32.955
As a developer, there are two questions I needed to answer. What should we automate, and how should we automate it?


12
00:02:32.955 --> 00:02:42.955
Threat hunting is reminiscent of trying to find a needle in a haystack, a magnitude of data that looks normal to the untrained eye, but the attack is written in between the lines.


13
00:02:42.955 --> 00:02:58.955
A Datadog are hunters search through a massive volume of logs from many different sources with varying schemas. It's really tedious to figure out which queries will surface the antenna data. And these queries are really important because they eventually become detection rules.


14
00:02:58.955 --> 00:03:09.955
That's why we mainly decided to automate query generation, since log data is represented as text, it seemed like an obvious use case for LLMs.


15
00:03:09.955 --> 00:03:16.955
This was our first question. Are modern LLMs good at threat hunting out of the box? If this is true, my job would be super easy.


16
00:03:16.955 --> 00:03:31.955
And we started really simple. We used OpenAI's GPT-4.1 model in a single agent, equipped it with web search capabilities, and the AWS Knowledge MCP for searching CloudTrail schema documentation.


17
00:03:31.955 --> 00:03:42.955
In the system prompt, we link the Datadog syntax documentation and provided some threat hunting hypotheses to query examples and just said, hey, you're a threat hunting agent, do your thing.


18
00:03:42.955 --> 00:03:59.955
The results were okay, given a broad threat hunting prompt that agent would generate several specific hypotheses with corresponding Datadog Lucen queries. Response time was really fast, an average of five seconds. However, syntax error rate was quite high at 25%.


19
00:03:59.955 --> 00:04:15.955
Our hunters complained about the aggressive hypothesis production and the frequently misnamed fields and irrelevant values. They also wanted the agent to automatically rule out some false positives. For instance, if the service logs are associated with a known testing account.


20
00:04:15.955 --> 00:04:36.955
It should interpret that. In summary, the major failures of our first iteration were low syntax accuracy, low semantic accuracy. So this means that the query does not surface the antenna data because the fields are wrong. I'm gonna be talking about schema and saying the word schema, like, a thousand times in this talk.


21
00:04:36.955 --> 00:04:42.955
But this is really the crux of our work on this tool.


22
00:04:42.955 --> 00:04:57.955
It also struggled with low relevance, so it wasn't using the data to drive conclusions, and we attributed a lot of this to ineffective tool usage. It was just ignoring whatever tools we provided it.


23
00:04:57.955 --> 00:05:03.955
We concluded that LLMs are bad at threat hunting, and we had to go back to the basics and understand what their capabilities actually were.


24
00:05:03.955 --> 00:05:15.955
LLMs are good at… Synthesis, pattern matching, and translation. We needed to focus on reducing threat hunting into problems of these categories.


25
00:05:15.955 --> 00:05:23.955
Before I get into the second iteration of the Hunting Copilot, I have to address the obvious obstacle in the AI threat hunting space, and that's data.


26
00:05:23.955 --> 00:05:27.955
Let's start with the nature of the log data we're querying.


27
00:05:27.955 --> 00:05:43.955
At Datadog, we have large volumes of telemetry with look-back periods of up to 450 days. And these logs are composed of faceted fields, which are indexed and easy to filter on, and many unfaceted fields. These are raw attributes that can be searched, but they aren't indexed.


28
00:05:43.955 --> 00:05:57.955
And this is what makes capturing the full schema of a source or index in a small number of tokens very challenging. It's even harder to understand what kinds of values exist for each field without actually querying the data.


29
00:05:57.955 --> 00:06:09.955
We also have customizable ingestion pipelines that increase automation complexity. And finally, threat hunting in general is hard to capture concretely because the success criteria is very ambiguous.


30
00:06:09.955 --> 00:06:16.955
The inputs, outputs, and methods used differ greatly from hunt to hunt and hunter to hunter.


31
00:06:16.955 --> 00:06:26.955
Fundamentally, this means we don't have a reliable ground truth readily available, neither for query generation nor for overall threat hunting.


32
00:06:26.955 --> 00:06:49.955
We thought about fine-tuning our agent before anyone asked, and the solution only makes sense if you have access to good threat hunting data. By good data, I mean data that is representative, well-labeled, and in abundance. We did not already have a well-curated corpus of past threat hunts with consistent inputs and outputs labeled in a way that can apply to unseen hunts.


33
00:06:49.955 --> 00:07:06.955
Given the amount of time and resources it would have taken to produce this, and the fact that we needed to deliver results quickly, we decided to stick to advanced prompt engineering techniques. Fine-tuning was just too high risk and high effort with expected low return.


34
00:07:06.955 --> 00:07:25.955
This is the point in our journey where we had to reframe the problem. Our hunters needed this agent to be accurate and useful. After syntax accuracy, semantic accuracy was the top weakness. And, in other words, queries that were syntactically valid were still answering the wrong question.


35
00:07:25.955 --> 00:07:40.955
So we reframed the problem around field discovery. We sat down with our threat hunters and asked them to walk us through how they analyze logs in a hunt. We found that their process was fortunately repeatable. It's a mix of informed guessing, sampling, and iterative refinement.


36
00:07:40.955 --> 00:07:52.955
They start with an initial hypothesis and broad queries. They dive into the raw logs and inspect sample values. Then they tweak their query and repeat this process until they find something valuable.


37
00:07:52.955 --> 00:08:03.955
We call this process log schema exploration. Instead of relying on documentation as a source of truth, the schema should be derived directly from the data.


38
00:08:03.955 --> 00:08:14.955
We shifted the boundary more towards AI with automated data analysis. So use the data to drive conclusions. And this would address the hunter's request to rule out some false positives as well.


39
00:08:14.955 --> 00:08:39.955
There were several sub-iterations that led to V2, but the core shift was towards a multi-agent framework. We introduced reasoning models such as GPT-5.1, and implemented an orchestrator expert framework. We also added the Datadog MCP server, and this allowed the agent to execute the queries it generated and then validate them against real logs. One of the most valuable features of this.


40
00:08:39.955 --> 00:08:46.955
is that it returns concise corrections when something is wrong, and that was the key to improving syntax accuracy.


41
00:08:46.955 --> 00:09:02.955
Lastly, we tightened the system prompt and defined iterative query refinement behaviors, as well as stop conditions. And we noticed that the agent struggled with tricky syntax, like negation or JSON policy document formatting, which our threat hunters love to search on.


42
00:09:02.955 --> 00:09:11.955
and wildcard placement. So we provided more concrete construction rules in this case for that.


43
00:09:11.955 --> 00:09:26.955
This is an overview of the architecture. We have the orchestrator, it's handling the investigation flow, maintaining the overall hunt context. It then gathers source documentation from expert subagents, such as for AWS CloudTrail or GCP audit logs.


44
00:09:26.955 --> 00:09:44.955
It then calls the Datadog agent, and it's essentially a wrapper for the Datadog MCP. It generates an iteratively refines queries based on the data. We notice that queries that return zero results were most likely semantically incorrect. So we just biased the agent towards generating logs results.


45
00:09:44.955 --> 00:09:53.955
Our stop conditions were both quantitative, so cap the number of iterations at 5, and subjective. If you find logs and can reach a conclusion, stop iterating.


46
00:09:53.955 --> 00:10:02.955
This divide-and-conquer approach reduced overall context load, um, context overload, and made each step more controlled and precise.


47
00:10:02.955 --> 00:10:20.955
With this architecture, we noticed a huge improvement in syntax accuracy by 17%, and slightly better semantic accuracy, but tool usage increased. All this, however, was at the cost of response speed. We went from an average of 5 seconds per response to 6 minutes, some edge cases taking.


48
00:10:20.955 --> 00:10:42.955
30 minutes to an hour. Our users were not happy with this response time, and semantic accuracy was still hindered by persistent hallucination. This was because query execution's often timed out, or the results were truncated. Sampling log data was just too computationally exhaustive to be handled by the agent alone.


49
00:10:42.955 --> 00:10:56.955
We learned a lot about the trade-offs of multi-agent frameworks and powerful MCP tools with V2, and it all comes down to context. This principle hasn't changed. Threat hunting workflows overload context if you manage the context well, you'll see results improve.


50
00:10:56.955 --> 00:11:06.955
The core lessons from V2 were that we should use reasoning sparingly. It was way too slow for production use cases, and if you use it, you should provide reasoning transparency to the user.


51
00:11:06.955 --> 00:11:17.955
Multi-agent frameworks are an excellent way to manage context. So the orchestrator is building context over the course of a hunt, but each expert agent, it starts fresh every time it's called.


52
00:11:17.955 --> 00:11:25.955
Based on how you conquer and divide, these sub-agents can become excellent at their specific task, and you save context space for the overall hunt.


53
00:11:25.955 --> 00:11:33.955
However, delegation introduces its own cost. Every handoff adds latency, and agent coordination will increase complexity.


54
00:11:33.955 --> 00:11:45.955
A quick note on chaining. We noticed that chains of length over 3 were subject to getting stuck downstream, especially if there was some looping, and that's what we had with the iterative refinement in the Datadog agent.


55
00:11:45.955 --> 00:11:50.955
So we try to keep our architecture at three layers or less.


56
00:11:50.955 --> 00:12:06.955
Tools are crucial, but they need to be concise and informative. We design tools to return short suggestions to take the burden of correction off of the agent, and we always specified a concise list of allowed tools for MCP servers that expose many.


57
00:12:06.955 --> 00:12:11.955
The system prompt should describe which tool should be called at which step.


58
00:12:11.955 --> 00:12:39.955
And I am aware of the very fickle nature of making bold claims on what AI can and cannot do. I did see the talks yesterday, especially Anthropic, Nicholas, Opus 4.5 and 4.6 were released quite recently. So Ozzy's LLMs get more powerful and the context window increases. You can simplify your architecture while keeping hallucinations low. But I'd argue that right now for threat hunting, multi-agent frameworks are still necessary for the best results.


59
00:12:39.955 --> 00:12:49.955
Achieving high query syntax accuracy was pretty easy. But semantic accuracy is really hard because of the high volume and density of the data.


60
00:12:49.955 --> 00:13:03.955
There are four fundamental approaches that we've been exploring to manage this. So the first is external documentation and AI. It's basically you're trying to make an educated guess on what the schema may look like at Datadog. And in practice, this wasn't very representative of the data.


61
00:13:03.955 --> 00:13:15.955
Law clustering and aggregations, they can really help cut down the logs that need to be analyzed. However, it's very easy to misjudge which facets to aggregate on, and the agent usually guesses wrong.


62
00:13:15.955 --> 00:13:29.955
The built-in clustering within the Datadog logs platform, if you've seen it, it's based on the message body or status. And that's not always relevant to the hunts. Our hunters love aggregating on super niche facets and attributes.


63
00:13:29.955 --> 00:13:45.955
We could preprocess with ingestion pipeline data. So build an understanding of schema statically. We gather all the remappers and grok parsers from the configuration pipeline, and then we feed that into the context, but it still misses some information and it's consuming a lot of context space.


64
00:13:45.955 --> 00:14:03.955
And it's also subject to change, so we still need a more dynamic approach. That would be live sampling. Dynamically learn schema from the data. And again, this is computationally exhaustive. So we had to shift the expectation of handling this away from AI agents and towards the tools.


65
00:14:03.955 --> 00:14:14.955
Our solution is a sort of coordinated dance amongst all of these options, and we fortify and tweak reliance on each one based on the performance that we're seeing.


66
00:14:14.955 --> 00:14:29.955
Okay, evaluations. A pretty painstaking, so undeniably important topic. The data problem I mentioned earlier, it applies here. We do not have a well-curated corpus of threat hunting data for a traditional evaluation system.


67
00:14:29.955 --> 00:14:44.955
Even when we generated that data, we noticed that evaluation results were not reflective of its performance in unseen hands. These traditional evaluation systems with inputs and expected outputs, they just produced a bunch of statistics. And oftentimes they showed high accuracy for certain tasks.


68
00:14:44.955 --> 00:14:50.955
But our users disagreed. So, passing evaluations did not always correlate with trust.


69
00:14:50.955 --> 00:15:11.955
A single number to capture the performance can be quite misleading. Like, claiming that an agent is 95% accurate, that could mean anything. And it makes you think that it'll be accurate 95% of the time in future hunts. What matters is it's the data, rubrics and scoring mechanisms behind the evaluation mechanism that actually carries the truth. And so.


70
00:15:11.955 --> 00:15:17.955
There's this trade-off between the time invested into a robust evaluation system and developing the tool.


71
00:15:17.955 --> 00:15:25.955
Especially given the size of our team. So, we invested time into other eval strategies.


72
00:15:25.955 --> 00:15:40.955
Our strategy was to prioritize trends, comparative metrics, and human feedback over static benchmark performance. We conducted A-B testing during our hunt weeks, so human versus machine. Some hunters use the tool, and others didn't, and we compared their respective results.


73
00:15:40.955 --> 00:15:53.955
We rely on a frequent and tight user feedback loop, and also collect data as the hunters use the tool to figure out when and how they choose to use it. Because for us, usage corresponded to success.


74
00:15:53.955 --> 00:16:13.955
We pruned non-essential evaluation metrics and distilled it down to a few tasks that traditional benchmarking made sense for, like response speed or syntax accuracy, because we have, like, a Datadog syntax validation checker. For semantic accuracy, we're not just pinning an LLM-based judge against it, like, that would be circular, because we just… I just argued that LLMs aren't very skilled at that.


75
00:16:13.955 --> 00:16:33.955
What we do instead is that we run the agent on our test prompts, and we extract the unique queries, and then we run them to see the results. For the test cases that didn't have any results, we would do a lot of manual verification. And we did, you know, we did add an LLM judge on that, but it's kind of a combination of different… Tactics as opposed to just…


76
00:16:33.955 --> 00:16:39.955
What does LLM-based judge think, um, off the bat?


77
00:16:39.955 --> 00:16:51.955
All right. So that was kind of the preface and how we built it, and now I want to walk through how our tool aided our hunters in a recent AWS privilege escalation hunt week.


